      Tesla BitcoinI  wrote back in February:A funny thing for Elon Musk to=
 do would be:1. Tesla Inc. buys some Bitcoin.2. Tesla announces that Bitcoi=
n is good now and that it bought some.3. The price of Bitcoin goes up, beca=
use institutional adoption of Bitcoin is good for its price, but also becau=
se, by the Elon Markets Hypothesis, anything that Musk buys goes up.4. Tesl=
a sells some Bitcoin, making a profit.5. Musk tweets that the price of Bitc=
oin is too high.6. Bitcoin prices go down due to the Elon Markets Hypothesi=
s.7. Go to Step 1.Well, on Monday Tesla announced earnings, and  guess what=
 guess what guess what:Tesla pulled a new lever to juice earnings in the qu=
arter, generating $101 million in income from selling about 10% of its Bitc=
oin holdings.Profit from the cryptocurrency and the sale of regulatory cred=
its and tax benefits contributed about 25 cents to Tesla=E2=80=99s adjusted=
 earnings of 93 cents a share, allowing the carmaker to beat Wall Street=E2=
=80=99s 80-cent average estimate, Dan Levy, an analyst with Credit Suisse, =
wrote in a note Monday.That=E2=80=99s wonderful, my sincere congratulations=
 to them. People want to be mad about this? There is a vague sense out ther=
e that it is somehow fraud to buy a thing, say you like it, and then sell s=
ome of it. For instance Dave Portnoy, who I guess is an investment celebrit=
y now, used the words =E2=80=9Cpumps=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cdumps=E2=80=9D t=
o describe Tesla=E2=80=99s actions on Twitter, prompting Musk to reply that=
 =E2=80=9CTesla sold 10% of its holdings essentially to prove liquidity of =
Bitcoin as an alternative to holding cash on balance sheet.=E2=80=9D (Tesla=
=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CMaster of Coin,=E2=80=9D Chief Financial Officer Zachar=
y Kirkhorn, also talked a lot about liquidity on the earnings call; Tesla d=
ecided to put a chunk of its corporate cash into Bitcoin and I guess needed=
 to make sure that its money wasn=E2=80=99t trapped. A reasonable concern! =
=E2=80=9CWe've been quite pleased with how much liquidity there is in the B=
itcoin market,=E2=80=9D said Kirkhorn.)For myself, I want to be absolutely =
clear that:=09I don=E2=80=99t think there=E2=80=99s anything illegal about =
Tesla buying Bitcoin, saying that it bought Bitcoin, and then selling Bitco=
in when the price goes up. There=E2=80=99s no indication that Tesla, or Mus=
k, were lying=C2=A0about any of this. (Not legal advice!)=09I think that's =
cool and fun, I=E2=80=99m glad they did it, and I hope they=E2=80=99ll do i=
t again.=09I think that, if you can reliably do that =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you =
are Elon Musk and you can make Bitcoin go up by tweeting about it =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0you almost have an obligation to do it? Perhaps a fiduciary obligatio=
n to your shareholders, but at least a sort of aesthetic obligation to come=
dy. If Bitcoin wants Musk to manipulate it, Musk really ought to manipulate=
 it.As I  wrote in February, when Tesla bought the Bitcoins:Musk is in the =
nice position of being able to spend billions of dollars buying assets in l=
iquid anonymous markets, and then make those assets go up just by tweeting =
about them. If you can do that, you should! If you can buy a thing secretly=
, announce =E2=80=9CI own the thing,=E2=80=9D reliably cause the thing=E2=
=80=99s price to go up a lot, and then =E2=80=94 if you want =E2=80=94 sell=
 the thing secretly, then that=E2=80=99s a great business right there. Talk=
 about clean energy; that=E2=80=99s a perpetual motion machine.Or people ha=
ve a sense that these earnings are somehow fake, less real than earnings fr=
om making and selling cars? The New York Times says=C2=A0that the Bitcoin s=
ales =E2=80=9Cled to a $101 million accounting boost,=E2=80=9D which makes =
it sound like it=E2=80=99s not an=C2=A0economic=C2=A0boost. But it is! That=
=E2=80=99s an extra $101 million of real U.S. dollars that came in the door=
 from selling Bitcoin for a profit.Actually the economic profit is signific=
antly greater than that. At Fortune, Shawn Tully estimates that Tesla bough=
t about 43,000 Bitcoins for $1.5 billion, about $34,700 per Bitcoin, in lat=
e January and early February, and sold about 4,800 for $272 million, about =
$55,100 per Bitcoin, in March.[1] That generated a $101 million profit on t=
he Bitcoins it sold =E2=80=94=C2=A0meaning that it paid $171 million and go=
t $272 million for them =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it also left Tesla with about 38=
,000 Bitcoins, for which it paid about $1.3 billion. It carries those Bitco=
ins on its balance sheet at its cost =E2=80=94=C2=A0at $1,331 million, to b=
e precise =E2=80=94=C2=A0but they=E2=80=99re worth a lot more than that now=
. (Roughly $2.1 billion at today=E2=80=99s price of about $54,750, or rough=
ly $2.26=C2=A0billion at $58,960 per Bitcoin, the price at the end of Tesla=
=E2=80=99s first quarter on March 31.)=C2=A0Tesla didn=E2=80=99t make $101 =
million on Bitcoin in the first quarter of 2021; it made about $1 billion o=
n Bitcoin. It=E2=80=99s just that most of those gains =E2=80=94=C2=A0more t=
han $900 million =E2=80=94=C2=A0were unrealized, and so don=E2=80=99t count=
 for accounting purposes. We  discussed corporate Bitcoin accounting in Feb=
ruary, and I pointed out that it=E2=80=99s somewhat odd for a financial ass=
et: When your Bitcoins go up, you don=E2=80=99t book a gain, but when they =
go down you do book a loss. The only way to book a gain on Bitcoins is to s=
ell them.This also means that Tesla is sitting on $900 million of unrealize=
d Bitcoin profit that it could realize any time it=E2=80=99s convenient. As=
 long as the price stays high. Which, fortunately for Tesla, is kind of in =
Elon Musk=E2=80=99s control!Obviously if you are a transformative electric =
car company it is=C2=A0better=C2=A0to make your profits by selling transfor=
mative electric cars than by moving the price of cryptocurrency with your t=
weets. Selling the cars is better for the environment, better for the world=
; it has higher growth potential; it deserves a higher multiple. My point i=
s only that, for Elon Musk right now, moving the price of cryptocurrency wi=
th his tweets is really easy and lucrative and, in the short term,=C2=A0sus=
tainable. Among the things he tweets about, it is probably the one that dis=
tracts him least from his work, and the one with the highest returns for sh=
areholders. He should do it every quarter.The deliThis does not sound like =
a very good deli:=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ve never been there,=E2=80=9D said Tina=
 Kauffman, who lives two doors down. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ve lived here five =
years, and it=E2=80=99s never open.=E2=80=9D=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ve come here=
 seven, eight times,=E2=80=9D added Paulsboro resident Ken Snyder. =E2=80=
=9COnly one time it was open. But they said the cook was out.=E2=80=9DOn a =
recent Saturday, at an hour when the deli=E2=80=99s Facebook page said it w=
ould be open, the doors were locked. A woman inside said it was closed for =
a =E2=80=9Cprivate event.=E2=80=9D She declined to say when the deli would =
be open next or how to contact the owners.Many neighbors living within a fe=
w blocks of the deli refused to talk about it at all. A man raking stones i=
n his yard told me he had never been to the deli, but declined to give his =
name because =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t want someone throwing blocks through =
my windows.=E2=80=9DThat is from this Fast Company article by Michael Linho=
rst about Your Hometown Deli, the Paulsboro, New Jersey, deli that  became =
famous because it is also a  $2 billion public company called Hometown Inte=
rnational Inc.[2] A crucial takeaway from the article is probably that, if=
=C2=A0it was a very good deli =E2=80=94=C2=A0if it was open at regular hour=
s, and the cook was there, and the food was good, and the neighbors liked i=
t, and nobody worried about getting a brick through their window=C2=A0for t=
alking about the deli=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0it would not be worth $2 billion?=
 Like, =E2=80=9Cdeli=E2=80=9D is a pretty established and well-understood s=
ort of business, and presumably there is some going rate for delis, some mu=
ltiple of sales or whatever. Hometown has sales of about $14,000 per year. =
Let=E2=80=99s say if it was good and open every day that would be 200 times=
 higher, $2.8 million a year,  a McDonald=E2=80=99s-ish number. Even if del=
is trade at 10 times revenues =E2=80=94=C2=A0which seems very high! =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0that gets you a $28 million deli, not $2 billion.But instead it is=
 a virtually nonexistent deli, which is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0more =E2=80=A6=C2=A0=
interesting?=C2=A0Publicly traded shell companies are strange entities. The=
y have stock and shareholders, but no significant assets or business activi=
ties. Sometimes they=E2=80=99re the remnants of a failed company=E2=80=94a =
zombie business whose corporate husk lives on. Other times, shells are crea=
ted that way from the start: They=E2=80=99re useful, and potentially profit=
able, because they can help a private company go public without having to d=
eal with the expense or scrutiny that comes with an IPO. The shell and the =
private company will merge, and the newly public company, now with real bus=
iness activity, will be able to raise money by issuing additional stock.But=
 companies that are created as shells from the start face numerous restrict=
ions, many of them aimed at curbing money laundering. The money they bring =
in from stock sales has to be held in escrow, not touched until the shell m=
erges with a private company. The shareholders can=E2=80=99t sell their sha=
res until the merger is done. The shell has an 18-month time limit to find =
a company to merge with and must file detailed public disclosures within da=
ys of any merger taking place.It=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Ceasier and better to me=
rge with an operating business than a shell,=E2=80=9D said David Feldman, a=
 corporate and securities lawyer at the firm Hiller, PC. That=E2=80=99s why=
 some bad actors use operating businesses to commit fraud. Feldman gave the=
 example of a small yoga studio, not making much money, that decides to go =
public. That=E2=80=99s fine, legally speaking. But if the owners don=E2=80=
=99t tell the public their real plan is to find a merger partner and shut d=
own the yoga studio? =E2=80=9CThat=E2=80=99s fraud,=E2=80=9D Feldman explai=
ned. =E2=80=9CEverybody who buys the stock of that company is misled about =
what its real business is.=E2=80=9DThe theory, which we have  discussed bef=
ore, is that if you have a public company with (1) good, proper, current Se=
curities and Exchange Commission filings and (2) not much in the way of a b=
usiness, that is an attractive merger target for a private company that wou=
ld like access to U.S.=C2=A0public stock markets without the scrutiny of an=
 initial public offering. Some private company would pay up to merge with t=
hat sort of a public company, quickly get rid of its small operating busine=
ss and use its public status to raise money. Linhorst finds some other comp=
anies that have some connections to Hometown=E2=80=99s shareholders, that p=
ay those shareholders thousands of dollars for vague consulting services, a=
nd that seem to be shell companies hunting for merger targets.Still, =E2=80=
=9Cpay up=E2=80=9D means, like, a few million dollars? Like, this deli shou=
ld command a higher price than any other money-losing deli, because it has =
a public company with current U.S. securities filings attached to it, so it=
 can be used to take a company public. That can be worth money, to a smalli=
sh shady-ish company that would like to go public. It can=E2=80=99t be wort=
h $2 billion. Even the shadiest company can find a way to go public for les=
s than $2 billion.I still don=E2=80=99t know what=E2=80=99s going on with t=
he deli, and I don=E2=80=99t really want a brick through my window either, =
but the obvious explanations don=E2=80=99t really work. =E2=80=9CShell comp=
any for a reverse merger scheme=E2=80=9D is perfectly fine as a theory, and=
 it would explain some of the corporate mechanics, but it does not explain =
a $2 billion (or, fine, $100 million) valuation. =E2=80=9CPump-and-dump to =
sell lots of stock to retail investors=E2=80=9D has the right basic shape, =
but there=E2=80=99s been no pumping =E2=80=94=C2=A0nobody at the deli has b=
een touting it, and it=E2=80=99s only in the news because David Einhorn wro=
te an investor letter about how bad it is =E2=80=94=C2=A0and no dumping: Th=
e stock barely trades, and nobody is getting rich by selling it to retail i=
nvestors.=C2=A0Occasionally in the crypto world you see=C2=A0parody project=
s to get a really high market capitalization for a really silly coin. The j=
oke is obvious. You create a new token, you issue 1 trillion tokens to your=
self, you sell 0.001 tokens to your buddy for $1, and, bam, your token has=
=C2=A0a $1 quadrillion market cap and your holdings are worth $999,999,999,=
999,999. And then you post about it on Medium and everyone is like =E2=80=
=9Clol nice one, market cap is a flawed way to measure the aggregate value =
of something that doesn=E2=80=99t trade very much or at arm=E2=80=99s lengt=
h.=E2=80=9D It is understood to be an art project, a commentary on post-mod=
ern capitalism, rather than a real economic thing. Nobody thinks your token=
 is =E2=80=9Cworth=E2=80=9D $1 quadrillion; that=E2=80=99s just its market =
cap.I know nothing about the deli but I prefer to imagine that it=E2=80=99s=
 that sort of art project. There it is, off in New Jersey, a deli that is n=
ever open with a stock that never trades, but that is somehow a $2 billion =
public company, just because it can be.


