Tax lawI  like to  cite, around here, Michael Graetz=E2=80=99s two laws of =
tax: It is always better to make more money than less money, and it is alwa=
ys better to die later than sooner. But I am always excited to find excepti=
ons. One important, but sometimes violated, corollary of the first law is t=
hat it=C2=A0should=C2=A0never be in your=C2=A0financial=C2=A0interest to gi=
ve money away. If you have $100 and you give it to charity, you (1) are out=
 $100 but (2) have a $100 tax deduction. If you have a lot of income and yo=
ur tax rate is 40%, that deduction should save you $40. Net, you are out $6=
0.But you can do a bit better than that. Let's say that you have stock in y=
our company that you got for $0 (you were the founder, etc.) and that is no=
w worth $100. If you sell it, you will get $100, all of which will be taxab=
le as capital gains. Let=E2=80=99s say the capital gains rate is 20%; you=
=E2=80=99ll get $80. If instead you donate it to charity, you won=E2=80=99t=
 have the $80, but you will get a $100 tax deduction that you can use again=
st your ordinary income. If your tax rate (the marginal rate on your ordina=
ry income) is 40%, that should save you $40. Eighty is more than 40 so this=
 is not a good trade, but it=E2=80=99s closer.If the top marginal rate on c=
apital gains,=C2=A0plus=C2=A0the top marginal rate on ordinary income, add =
up to more than 100%, though, you should donate. President Joe Biden has pr=
oposed significantly raising the top rate on capital gains, which creates t=
hat possibility. Here is a tweet by Andrew Granato (via Tyler Cowen) pointi=
ng out that =E2=80=9Cunder a 40% top federal marginal capital gains rate an=
d 40% top federal income tax rate with 13% top state rates for each, a taxp=
ayer in the top marginal bracket *gains post-tax money* by donating unreali=
zed capital gains to charity instead of realizing the gain.=E2=80=9D The ma=
th is pretty simple. If you own stock worth $100 with zero basis, and you s=
ell it, you pay 53% total taxes and keep $47. If instead you donate it, you=
 get a $100 tax deduction, which should save you $53 on your income taxes (=
assuming you have lots of ordinary income with a marginal tax rate, state p=
lus federal, of 53%). And 53 is more than 47, so this is a good trade and y=
ou should donate the stock.I should say:=09There are limitations on this: Y=
ou can=E2=80=99t shelter all of your income by donating appreciated stock, =
it assumes you have zero-basis stock and lots of ordinary income, etc., but=
 conceptually at some margin it seems correct. (Also: Not tax or legal advi=
ce!)=09I suppose the =E2=80=9Cunintended consequence=E2=80=9D of this will =
be to push startup founders to donate more of their stock to charity, and s=
ell less of it to buy houses, which doesn=E2=80=99t sound especially terrib=
le, though I suppose there could be bad consequences. (People who really li=
ke buying houses will be less likely to start startups, some charities will=
 be bad, etc.)=09I am telling you about it strictly as a possible violation=
 of the first law of tax, which I think is aesthetically interesting. I do =
not think that the first law of tax actually has to constrain policy makers=
.I should also say that,=C2=A0even under existing tax laws, you can get thi=
s sort of effect. The trick is:=09You have a zero-basis capital asset worth=
 $100. If you sell it, you get $100, pay 20% tax, keep $80. If you donate i=
t, you get a $100 tax deduction, which is worth $40 at a 40% tax rate.=09Bu=
t if you donate it=C2=A0and say it=E2=80=99s worth $300, you get a $300 tax=
 deduction, which is worth $120 at a 40% tax rate, and $120 is more than $8=
0.In practice this seems to be a huge deal in the art world, where works ar=
e non-fungible and value is subjective. If you sell a work of art, it=E2=80=
=99s worth what someone will pay you for it. But if you donate a work of ar=
t to a museum, it=E2=80=99s worth what you and the museum and an appraiser =
say it=E2=80=99s worth. You all have incentives to inflate that number, and=
 it is hard to check the market value of a unique piece of art that rarely =
trades. This is a well-known trick that sometimes=C2=A0gets people in troub=
le with the Internal Revenue Service.It is harder to do this sort of trick =
with stock, because there is generally=C2=A0a market price. But here is a c=
ool paper by=C2=A0Sureyya Burcu Avci, Cindy A. Schipani, H. Nejat Seyhun an=
d Andrew Verstein about =E2=80=9CInsider Giving=E2=80=9D:Corporate insiders=
 can avoid losses if they dispose of their stock while in possession of mat=
erial, non-public information. One means of disposal, selling the stock, is=
 illegal and subject to prompt mandatory reporting. A second strategy is al=
most as effective and it faces lax reporting requirements and legal restric=
tions. That second method is to donate the stock to a charity and take a ch=
aritable tax deduction at the inflated stock price. =E2=80=9CInsider giving=
=E2=80=9D is a potent substitute for insider trading. We show that insider =
giving is far more widespread than previously believed. In particular, we s=
how that it is not limited to officers and directors. Large investors appea=
r to regularly receive material non-public information and use it to avoid =
losses. Using a vast dataset of essentially all transactions in public comp=
any stock since 1986, we find consistent and economically significant evide=
nce that these shareholders=E2=80=99 impeccable timing likely reflects info=
rmation leakage. We also document substantial evidence of backdating =E2=80=
=93 investors falsifying the date of their gift to capture a larger tax bre=
ak. We show why lax reporting and enforcement encourage insider giving, exp=
lain why insider giving represents a policy failure, and highlight the theo=
retical implications of these findings to broader corporate, securities, an=
d tax debates.The theory is roughly:=09You have zero-basis stock that is =
=E2=80=9Creally=E2=80=9D worth $100, but that happens to be trading at $300=
 right now because the market doesn't know the bad news that you know. If y=
ou sell it, you get $300, pay 20% tax, keep $240, and go to prison for insi=
der trading. Or you can wait until the news is public, sell it for $100, pa=
y 20% tax, keep $80 and avoid prison.=09But if you donate it=C2=A0while it=
=E2=80=99s still trading at $300, you get a $300 tax deduction, which is wo=
rth $120, which is more than $80. And you don=E2=80=99t go to prison becaus=
e you never traded the stock while you had inside information.In general I=
=E2=80=99m an =E2=80=9Calways better to have more money than less money=E2=
=80=9D guy, but it=E2=80=99s good to know the exceptions.JPMorgan BitcoinOk=
ay:JPMorgan Chase is preparing to offer an actively managed bitcoin fund to=
 certain clients, becoming the latest, largest and =E2=80=93 if its CEO=E2=
=80=99s well-documented distaste for bitcoin is any indication =E2=80=93 un=
likeliest U.S. mega-bank to embrace crypto as an asset class. =C2=A0The JPM=
organ bitcoin fund could roll out as soon as this summer, two sources famil=
iar with the matter told CoinDesk. Institutional bitcoin shop NYDIG will se=
rve as JPMorgan=E2=80=99s custody provider, a third source said.JPMorgan=E2=
=80=99s bitcoin fund will be actively managed, multiple sources told CoinDe=
sk. That=E2=80=99s a notable break from the passive fare offered by crypto =
industry stalwarts like Pantera Capital and Galaxy Digital, which let well-=
heeled clients buy and hold bitcoin through funds without ever touching it =
themselves. Galaxy and NYDIG are now offering bitcoin funds to Morgan Stanl=
ey clients.The JPMorgan fund will be for private wealth clients, a source f=
amiliar with the situation told CoinDesk.I realize that it is a popular cat=
egory but I still am not fully sure what an actively managed Bitcoin fund=
=C2=A0is? Like, you give JPMorgan $100, and they invest somewhere between $=
0 and $200 in Bitcoin for you? And adjust that amount over time? So you are=
 exposed to (1) the price of Bitcoin and (2) JPMorgan=E2=80=99s market timi=
ng decisions about Bitcoin? I guess I can see the appeal of that. It=E2=80=
=99s not for crypto die-hards, obviously, but =E2=80=9Cgive me=C2=A0Bitcoin=
, but only to the extent Jamie Dimon thinks Bitcoin is okay now=E2=80=9D ac=
tually is a pretty intuitive desire. If you are aware that Bitcoin is buzzy=
 and going up a lot, but don=E2=80=99t entirely trust it, but=C2=A0do=C2=A0=
trust your JPMorgan private wealth manager, perhaps you will want precisely=
 a JPMorgan-determined amount of Bitcoin exposure.Still, it seems awkward t=
o run a Bitcoin fund that=E2=80=99s not fully invested in Bitcoin. If you r=
un the Bitcoin fund and it=E2=80=99s 20% in Bitcoin as Bitcoin rips up, you=
=E2=80=99re going to get some hard questions. And if it=E2=80=99s 20% in Bi=
tcoin as Bitcoin crashes, people are going to take their money out of the B=
itcoin fund anyway.DogecoinI=E2=80=99m just going to  file this here as, li=
ke, =E2=80=9Csign of a bubble=E2=80=9D or whatever:In an appearance on =E2=
=80=9CThe Ellen DeGeneres Show,=E2=80=9D the owner of the Dallas Mavericks =
NBA team [Mark Cuban] said the rise of the =E2=80=9Cmeme=E2=80=9D digital c=
urrency is the =E2=80=9Ccraziest story ever=E2=80=9D and tried to answer qu=
estions about the token represented by a smiling Shiba Inu.=E2=80=9COverall=
, when someone brings up Dogecoin to you and asks you if it=E2=80=99s a goo=
d investment, I would say it=E2=80=99s not the world=E2=80=99s best investm=
ent but it=E2=80=99s a whole lot better than a lottery ticket, and it=E2=80=
=99s a great way to learn and start understanding cryptocurrencies,=E2=80=
=9D Cuban said. =E2=80=9CAnd you know what? It could go up. And the second =
part about it is if it doesn=E2=80=99t go up and you want to spend it, you =
can buy merchandise on the Mavericks store.=E2=80=9DImagine if you asked yo=
ur broker =E2=80=9Cshould I buy GameStop Corp. stock=E2=80=9D and she repli=
ed =E2=80=9Cwell it is better than a lottery ticket, so yes.=E2=80=9D Hones=
tly my assumption is that that=E2=80=99s how a lot of people do think about=
 GameStop, or Dogecoin. The odds of those things going to zero=C2=A0soon=C2=
=A0are pretty low because they get a lot of attention; your lottery ticket =
will almost certainly go to zero in a few days. And only a few people will =
get rich off the lottery, while a lot of people=C2=A0have=C2=A0gotten rich =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0and more still might! =E2=80=94=C2=A0off meme stocks and cry=
ptos. If you set the bar really low =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9CI am just gambl=
ing for fun and fully expect to lose my money, whaddaya got for me?=E2=80=
=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0then a lot of things become attractive investments. The =
bar is not always that low! Right now it is.Things happenA rising actor, fa=
ke HBO deals and one of Hollywood=E2=80=99s most audacious Ponzi schemes.=
=C2=A0Archegos Hit Tops $10 Billion After UBS, Nomura Losses. US futures tr=
aders gorge on cheddar amid race to lock in supplies. Credit Suisse: plotti=
ng a comeback after =E2=80=98costly mistakes=E2=80=99 took it to the brink.=
 Dimon Signals to Wall Street It=E2=80=99s Time to  Return to the Office. U=
.S. watchdog mulls guidance to curb SPAC projections, liability shield. Ant=
 IPO-Approval Process Under Investigation by Beijing. Saudi Arabia to Sell =
More Aramco Stakes, Crown Prince Says.=C2=A0California Is Awash in Cash, Th=
anks to a Booming Market. Shipping Containers  Fall Overboard at Fastest Ra=
te in Seven Years. CEO of $2 Billion Startup Ousted for  Taking LSD at Work=
. This family built a massive dinosaur out of take-out containers during th=
eir hotel quarantine.=C2=A0Prancer, The 'Haunted Victorian Child' Dog From =
Viral Ad, Has Been Adopted.=C2=A0A Microsoft Excel influencer quit her day =
job and is making 6 figures from her unconventional way of teaching spreads=
heet hacks, tips, and tricks.If you'd like to get=C2=A0Money=C2=A0Stuff=C2=
