om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; padding-bottom: 5px; margin-top=
: 30px; margin-bottom: 0;">Tesla Bitcoin</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23679940.287738/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMjIvZWxl=
Y3RyaWMtYmlsbHMtYXJlLWEtZ2FtYmxlLXRvbw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBecfbeda1" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> wrote back=
 in February</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A funny thing=
 for Elon Musk to do would be:</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">1. Tesla Inc=
. buys some Bitcoin.<br />2. Tesla announces that Bitcoin is good now and t=
hat it bought some.<br />3. The price of Bitcoin goes up, because instituti=
onal adoption of Bitcoin is good for its price, but also because, by the El=
on Markets Hypothesis, anything that Musk buys goes up.<br />4. Tesla sells=
 some Bitcoin, making a profit.<br />5. Musk tweets that the price of Bitco=
in is too high.<br />6. Bitcoin prices go down due to the Elon Markets Hypo=
thesis.<br />7. Go to Step 1.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
Well, on Monday <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23=
679940.287738/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzEzMTg2M=
DUvMDAwMTU2NDU5MDIxMDIwNTU4L3RzbGEtZXg5OV8xMzYuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cB9daf4915" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
">Tesla announced earnings</a>, and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/23679940.287738/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDQtMjYvdGVzbGEtYmVhdHMtb24tcHJvZml0LWxlYXZlcy1kZWxpdmVy=
eS1vdXRsb29rLXVuY2hhbmdlZA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2a61b8c7" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> guess what guess what =
guess what</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Tesla pulled a =
new lever to juice earnings in the quarter, generating $101 million in inco=
me from selling about 10% of its Bitcoin holdings.</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">Profit from the cryptocurrency and the sale of regulatory credits a=
nd tax benefits contributed about 25 cents to Tesla=E2=80=99s adjusted earn=
ings of 93 cents a share, allowing the carmaker to beat Wall Street=E2=80=
=99s 80-cent average estimate, Dan Levy, an analyst with Credit Suisse, wro=
te in a note Monday.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=
=80=99s wonderful, my sincere congratulations to them. People want to be ma=
d about this? There is a vague sense out there that it is somehow fraud to =
buy a thing, say you like it, and then sell some of it. For instance Dave P=
ortnoy, who I guess is an investment celebrity now, <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23679940.287738/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvb=
S9zdG9vbHByZXNpZGVudGUvc3RhdHVzLzEzODY3OTc1NTE3OTQ0OTk1OTI/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cB17ea4a86" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;">used the words</a> =E2=80=9Cpumps=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cdumps=E2=
=80=9D to describe Tesla=E2=80=99s actions on Twitter, <a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23679940.287738/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLm=
NvbS9lbG9ubXVzay9zdGF0dXMvMTM4NjgyMTE0NDAzNzIzNjczNw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cBbd57d184" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;">prompting Musk to reply</a> that =E2=80=9CTesla sold 10% of its holdings=
 essentially to prove liquidity of Bitcoin as an alternative to holding cas=
h on balance sheet.=E2=80=9D (Tesla=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CMaster of Coin,=E2=
=80=9D Chief Financial Officer Zachary Kirkhorn, also talked a lot about li=
quidity on the earnings call; Tesla decided to put a chunk of its corporate=
 cash into Bitcoin and I guess needed to make sure that its money wasn=E2=
=80=99t trapped. A reasonable concern! =E2=80=9CWe've been quite pleased wi=
th how much liquidity there is in the Bitcoin market,=E2=80=9D said Kirkhor=
n.)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For myself, I want to be absolutely cle=
ar that:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; marg=
in: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">I don=E2=80=99t think the=
re=E2=80=99s anything illegal about Tesla buying Bitcoin, saying that it bo=
ught Bitcoin, and then selling Bitcoin when the price goes up. There=E2=80=
=99s no indication that Tesla, or Musk, were <em>lying=C2=A0</em>about any =
of this. (Not legal advice!)</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">I thi=
nk that's cool and fun, I=E2=80=99m glad they did it, and I hope they=E2=80=
=99ll do it again.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">I think that, i=
f you can reliably do that =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you are Elon Musk and you can =
make Bitcoin go up by tweeting about it =E2=80=94=C2=A0you almost have an o=
bligation to do it? Perhaps a fiduciary obligation to your shareholders, bu=
t at least a sort of aesthetic obligation to comedy. If Bitcoin wants Musk =
to manipulate it, Musk really ought to manipulate it.</li></ol><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">As I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/23679940.287738/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGV=
zLzIwMjEtMDItMDgvZWxvbi1tdXNrLXdvcmtzLWhpcy1tYWdpYy1vbi1kb2dlY29pbi1hbmQtYm=
l0Y29pbg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc8095992" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscop=
e=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> wrote in February</a>, when Tesla bought=
 the Bitcoins:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Musk is in the n=
ice position of being able to spend billions of dollars buying assets in li=
quid anonymous markets, and then make those assets go up just by tweeting a=
bout them. If you can do that, you should! If you can buy a thing secretly,=
 announce =E2=80=9CI own the thing,=E2=80=9D reliably cause the thing=E2=80=
=99s price to go up a lot, and then =E2=80=94 if you want =E2=80=94 sell th=
e thing secretly, then that=E2=80=99s a great business right there. Talk ab=
out clean energy; that=E2=80=99s a perpetual motion machine.</p></blockquot=
e><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or people have a sense that these earnings a=
re somehow fake, less real than earnings from making and selling cars? The =
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23679940.287738/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5jb20vMjAyMS8wNC8yNy9idXNpbmVzcy9kZWFsYm9vay90ZXNsY=
S1lYXJuaW5ncy1iaXRjb2luLmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB02691973" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">New York Times say=
s</a>=C2=A0that the Bitcoin sales =E2=80=9Cled to a $101 million accounting=
 boost,=E2=80=9D which makes it sound like it=E2=80=99s not an=C2=A0<em>eco=
nomic=C2=A0</em>boost. But it is! That=E2=80=99s an extra $101 million of r=
eal U.S. dollars that came in the door from selling Bitcoin for a profit.</=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Actually the economic profit is significantl=
y greater than that. At Fortune, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/23679940.287738/aHR0cHM6Ly9mb3J0dW5lLmNvbS8yMDIxLzA0LzI3L3Rl=
c2xhLXRzbGEtYml0Y29pbi1idGMtYmV0LWhvdy1tdWNoLWhhcy1pdC1tYWRlLWVsb24tbXVzay1=
wcm9maXRzLw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBffe4e882" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Shawn Tully estimates</a> that Tesla b=
ought about 43,000 Bitcoins for $1.5 billion, about $34,700 per Bitcoin, in=
 late January and early February, and sold about 4,800 for $272 million, ab=
out $55,100 per Bitcoin, in March.[1] That generated a $101 million profit =
on the Bitcoins it sold =E2=80=94=C2=A0meaning that it paid $171 million an=
d got $272 million for them =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it also left Tesla with abou=
t 38,000 Bitcoins, for which it paid about $1.3 billion. It carries those B=
itcoins on its balance sheet at its cost =E2=80=94=C2=A0at $1,331 million, =
to be precise =E2=80=94=C2=A0but they=E2=80=99re worth a lot more than that=
 now. (Roughly $2.1 billion at today=E2=80=99s price of about $54,750, or r=
oughly $2.26=C2=A0billion at $58,960 per Bitcoin, the price at the end of T=
esla=E2=80=99s first quarter on March 31.)=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">Tesla didn=E2=80=99t make $101 million on Bitcoin in the first quarte=
r of 2021; it made about $1 billion on Bitcoin. It=E2=80=99s just that most=
 of those gains =E2=80=94=C2=A0more than $900 million =E2=80=94=C2=A0were u=
nrealized, and so don=E2=80=99t count for accounting purposes. We <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23679940.287738/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMDgvZWxvbi1tdXNr=
LXdvcmtzLWhpcy1tYWdpYy1vbi1kb2dlY29pbi1hbmQtYml0Y29pbg/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cCc8095992" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;"> discussed corporate Bitcoin accounting in February</a>, and I pointed=
 out that it=E2=80=99s somewhat odd for a financial asset: When your Bitcoi=
ns go up, you don=E2=80=99t book a gain, but when they go down you do book =
a loss. The only way to book a gain on Bitcoins is to sell them.</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This also means that Tesla is sitting on $900 million=
 of unrealized Bitcoin profit that it could realize any time it=E2=80=99s c=
onvenient. As long as the price stays high. Which, fortunately for Tesla, i=
s kind of in Elon Musk=E2=80=99s control!</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">O=
bviously if you are a transformative electric car company it is=C2=A0<em>be=
tter=C2=A0</em>to make your profits by selling transformative electric cars=
 than by moving the price of cryptocurrency with your tweets. Selling the c=
ars is better for the environment, better for the world; it has higher grow=
th potential; it deserves a higher multiple. My point is only that, for Elo=
n Musk right now, moving the price of cryptocurrency with his tweets is rea=
lly easy and lucrative and, in the short term,=C2=A0sustainable. Among the =
things he tweets about, it is probably the one that distracts him least fro=
m his work, and the one with the highest returns for shareholders. He shoul=
d do it every quarter.</p><h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quo=
t;Arial Black&quot;, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; fo=
nt-size: 20px; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; paddi=
ng-bottom: 5px; margin-top: 30px; margin-bottom: 0;">The deli</h2><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This does not sound <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/23679940.287738/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZmFzdGNvbXBhbnkuY29t=
LzkwNjI5MDc1L3RoZS1jYXNlLW9mLXRoZS0xMDAtbWlsbGlvbi1kZWxp/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cB9ab04e2c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;">like a very good deli</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ve never been there,=E2=80=9D said Tina Kauffman, who=
 lives two doors down. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ve lived here five years, and it=
=E2=80=99s never open.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CI=
=E2=80=99ve come here seven, eight times,=E2=80=9D added Paulsboro resident=
 Ken Snyder. =E2=80=9COnly one time it was open. But they said the cook was=
 out.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On a recent Saturday, at an =
hour when the deli=E2=80=99s Facebook page said it would be open, the doors=
 were locked. A woman inside said it was closed for a =E2=80=9Cprivate even=
t.=E2=80=9D She declined to say when the deli would be open next or how to =
contact the owners.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Many neighbors living w=
ithin a few blocks of the deli refused to talk about it at all. A man rakin=
g stones in his yard told me he had never been to the deli, but declined to=
 give his name because =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t want someone throwing block=
s through my windows.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>That is from <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2367=
9940.287738/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZmFzdGNvbXBhbnkuY29tLzkwNjI5MDc1L3RoZS1jYXNlLW9=
mLXRoZS0xMDAtbWlsbGlvbi1kZWxp/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC9ab04e2c" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">this Fast Company =
article</a> by Michael Linhorst about Your Hometown Deli, the Paulsboro, Ne=
w Jersey, deli that <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/23679940.287738/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzL=
zIwMjEtMDQtMTkvZXZlcnlvbmUtbG92ZXMtdGhlLTEwMC1taWxsaW9uLW5ldy1qZXJzZXktZGVs=
aS1leGNlcHQtZGF2aWQtZWluaG9ybi1rbm90dHJtYg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB92adcfa=
9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> became=
 famous</a> because it is also a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/23679940.287738/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9u=
L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDQtMjAvaG9tZXRvd24taW50ZXJuYXRpb25hbC1uZXctamVyc2V5LWR=
lbGktaXMtYWN0dWFsbHktd29ydGgtMi1iaWxsaW9u/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBefe88349=
" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> $2 bill=
ion public company</a> called Hometown International Inc.[2] A crucial take=
away from the article is probably that, if=C2=A0it was a very good deli =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0if it was open at regular hours, and the cook was there, and th=
e food was good, and the neighbors liked it, and nobody worried about getti=
ng a brick through their window=C2=A0for talking about the deli=C2=A0=E2=80=
=94=C2=A0it would not be worth $2 billion? Like, =E2=80=9Cdeli=E2=80=9D is =
a pretty established and well-understood sort of business, and presumably t=
here is some going rate for delis, some multiple of sales or whatever. Home=
town has sales of about $14,000 per year. Let=E2=80=99s say if it was good =
and open every day that would be 200 times higher, $2.8 million a year, <a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23679940.287738/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9mZWF0dXJlcy8yMDE1LW1jZG9uYWxkcy1mcmFuY2hpc2Vz=
Lw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbdecfb3d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border=
-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: soli=
d; background-color: #ccc;"> a McDonald=E2=80=99s-ish number</a>. Even if d=
elis trade at 10 times revenues =E2=80=94=C2=A0which seems very high! =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0that gets you a $28 million deli, not $2 billion.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But instead it is a virtually nonexistent deli, which =
is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0more =E2=80=A6=C2=A0interesting?=C2=A0</p><blockquote><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Publicly traded shell companies are strange entit=
ies. They have stock and shareholders, but no significant assets or busines=
s activities. Sometimes they=E2=80=99re the remnants of a failed company=E2=
=80=94a zombie business whose corporate husk lives on. Other times, shells =
are created that way from the start: They=E2=80=99re useful, and potentiall=
y profitable, because they can help a private company go public without hav=
ing to deal with the expense or scrutiny that comes with an IPO. The shell =
and the private company will merge, and the newly public company, now with =
real business activity, will be able to raise money by issuing additional s=
tock.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But companies that are created as she=
lls from the start face numerous restrictions, many of them aimed at curbin=
g money laundering. The money they bring in from stock sales has to be held=
 in escrow, not touched until the shell merges with a private company. The =
shareholders can=E2=80=99t sell their shares until the merger is done. The =
shell has an 18-month time limit to find a company to merge with and must f=
ile detailed public disclosures within days of any merger taking place.</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Ceasier and better to mer=
ge with an operating business than a shell,=E2=80=9D said David Feldman, a =
corporate and securities lawyer at the firm Hiller, PC. That=E2=80=99s why =
